1f971.title: Yawning Face
1f971.description: A yellow face with eyes closed and mouth wide open covered by a hand. Captured mid-yawn, this may represent having insufficient sleep, or to imply boredom with a person or topic. Not to be confused with 😪 Sleepy Face or 😴 Sleeping Face, which often convey actually being asleep, or 😫 Tired Face which is tired as in "fed up". Yawning Face was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

1f9a7.title: Orangutan
1f9a7.description: An orangutan, the orange-haired ape with long arms. Depicted facing forward, with a long broad face and sitting with its legs bent. Often shown scratching its head. Skin color varies across platforms, ranging from light to dark. Google’s orangutan has purplish skin, Twitter's is smiling. Orangutan was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

1f9ae.title: Guide Dog
1f9ae.description: A guide (or Seeing Eye) dog, trained to help lead a person who is blind or visually impaired. Generally depicted as a yellowish-brown Labrador Retriever on all fours facing left, equipped with a harness and handle. Many platforms additionally include a collar. Not to be confused with 🐕‍🦺 Service Dog, though their popular applications may overlap. Twitter implements the same dog as its 🐕 Dog. Samsung and Twitter’s guide dogs have green harnesses. Guide Dog was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

1f415-200d-1f9ba.title: Service Dog
1f415-200d-1f9ba.description: A service animal displayed with a safety vest and lead. Differs from the guide dog as this animal is intended for detection of seizures or other “hidden disabilities”, according to the proposal from Apple. The Service Dog emoji is a sequence of the 🐕 Dog and 🦺 Safety Vest emojis. These are combined using a zero width joiner between each character and display as a single emoji on supported platforms. Service Dog was added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

1f9a5.title: Sloth
1f9a5.description: A sloth, the slow-moving, tree-dwelling mammal. Depicted as a light-brown sloth with a wide, whitish, masked face hanging from a tree branch, facing left or right. Generally shown as a three-toed sloth. Sloth was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

1f9a6.title: Otter
1f9a6.description: An otter, the playful water mammal in the weasel family. Depicted as a light-brown otter on its back, with its forepaws held together and whiskered face to the left, generally with its long tail curled up. Apple’s otter is in water, holding a stone, as is Microsoft’s. Otter was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

1f9a8.title: Skunk
1f9a8.description: A skunk, a bushy-tailed mammal that sprays a foul odor when threatened. Depicted in full profile on all fours facing left, with black hair and its distinctive white stripe running from its head down to a curled-up tail. Google’s skunk bears a humorously haughty air. Skunk was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.

1f9a9.title: Flamingo
1f9a9.description: A flamingo, a waterbird with pink feathers and long neck and legs. Depicted as a flamingo in full profile facing left, standing on one leg, usually with a long, black beak. May be used to represent summer fun or as a pink accent color. Flamingo was approved as part of Unicode 12.0 in 2019 and added to Emoji 12.0 in 2019.
